In comparison with the Eq.~(2) of the main text, we now exclude NNN couplings and add random static magnetic fields acting on each site $n$, the amplitudes $h_n$ being random numbers from a uniform distribution $[-h,h]$. As $h$ increases from zero, the level spacing distribution changes from Poisson to Wigner-Dyson. Level repulsion and chaotic eigenstates occur for $0<h\lesssim 1$. As $h$ is further increased beyond the coupling strength, $h>1$, level crossing is not prohibited anymore and the eigenstates become more localized in real space. 


The cases where $h>1$ were studied in Refs.~[35,36]. Here, we focus on the small values of $h$.
In the figure below we show the average of $F(t)$ over different disorder realizations and different initial states. The average is denoted by $\langle F(t) \rangle$. For each realization, we choose as initial states, 10\% of all ${\cal D}$ site-basis vectors whose energy $E_0 $ are closest to the middle of the spectrum of the disordered Hamiltonian. The total number of data for the average, including initial states and realizations, is $10^5$.

We see that for small disorder, $h=0.1$ [Fig.~\ref{fig:supp01} (a)] and $h=0.2$ [Fig.~\ref{fig:supp01} (b)], the initial Gaussian decay is followed by a powerlaw behavior $\propto t^{-2}$, as indicated by the dashed line. In contrast with the Fig.~1 of the main text, since several realizations are now taken into account, the fluctuations are averaged out and the $t^{-2}$ is very clear. As $h$ increases, the powerlaw exponent decreases, as visible in Fig.~\ref{fig:supp01} (c) (see also Refs.~[35,36] ).

